Can't you just implement finally in "userspace"?  In Perl, you can implement it with object destruction -- you make an instance of an object whose destructor does the cleanup you want, and when it goes out of scope (exception thrown, return, etc.), the cleanup code is run.<p>It's extremely common to write code like:<p><pre><code>    sub work_in_tmpdir(&) {
        my $cwd = cwd;
        my $guard = guard { chdir $cwd };
        chdir mktmp;
        $_[0]->();
    }
</code></pre>
Then you can safely work in a temporary directory:<p><pre><code>    print cwd; # /home/jon
    work_in_tmpdir { print cwd; die "OH NOES" }; # /tmp/3sdjkh387dh
    print cwd; # /home/jon
</code></pre>
If this doesn't look enough like Java, that's easy to fix:<p><pre><code>    sub try(&;@) {
        my ($code, %args) = @_;
        my $guard;
        $guard = guard { $args{finally}->() }
            if exists $args{finally};  
        my $result = eval { $code->() };
        if($args{catch} && !$result){
            $args{catch}->($@);
        }
        return $result;
    }
    catch(&;@) {
        return catch => @_;
    }
    finally(&) {
        return finally => $_[0];
    }
</code></pre>
(+) Now you can say:<p><pre><code>    try     { something_exceptional }
    catch   { warn "Something bad happened: $_[0] }
    finally { cleanup };
</code></pre>
No language feature or bug tracker rant-fest required!  And, I'm pretty sure that you can abuse destructors in PHP to get exactly the same result.  (In Perl, that "guard" function from the Guard module is implemented something like:   class Foo { has 'cleanup' => (is => 'ro', isa => CodeRef ); sub DESTROY {  $self->cleanup->() } }; sub guard(&){ return Foo->new( cleanup => $_[0] ) })<p>(+) Also, don't cut-n-paste this code into your apps.  It misses special cases.  use Try::Tiny, TryCatch, etc. from the CPAN.
